  "notes": [
    "v2 schema: each entry maps a source-language IPA fragment to a target-orthography respelling. The same source language can publish multiple target tables (es→en, es→pt, es→fr, ...). Target orthography rules are baked into the respelling values, not derived at runtime — the converter engine is intentionally dumb.",
    "Spanish→English target style (locked 2026-05-08 per Matt's 'spelled in English / following English conventions' brief): English readers should be able to read the respelling aloud and produce a passable approximation of the source. Reader-perception-driven, not phoneme-rigor-driven.",
    "Vowel rules: /a/→ah (open-A as in 'father'), /e/→ay (the diphthong 'say' is closer to Spanish /e/ than 'eh'), /i/→ee, /o/→oh, /u/→oo. Word-final unstressed -e becomes 'eh' to avoid silent-e: 'noche'→NOH-cheh, not NOH-chay.",
    "Consonant rules: /ð/→d (English readers don't naturally produce intervocalic 'th' here), /x/→h, /ɲ/→ny, /ʝ/ʎ/→y (yeísmo default), /tʃ/→ch, /ks/→ks. Trilled /r/ kept as 'rr' so the reader knows to roll. Tap /ɾ/ kept as 'r'.",
    "Word-final vowel+s patterns are kept as their own entries (-as→ahs, -os→ohs, -is→ees, -us→oos, -es→ays). Single-s respelling matches the parrot-lab corpus convention; the doubled-s 'BOSS not BOS' embellishment was dropped because medial 'as' substrings (e.g. 'casa') would over-fire it.",
    "Stress rendering: uppercase the stressed syllable (BWAY-nohss DEE-ahss). Syllable separator: '-'.",
    "Latin American Spanish is assumed: c/z/s all map to /s/; ll/y both map to /y/ (yeísmo). Castilian /θ/ deferred for now."
  ],
